WEBVTT

00:02.086 --> 00:03.711
Last week—

00:03.796 --> 00:05.838
Puck had to shave his Mohawk.
People started picking on him.

00:05.923 --> 00:07.965
He started dating Mercedes
to seem cool again
'cause she was on the Cheerios.

00:08.050 --> 00:09.717
- But then she quit.
- It's just not who I am.

00:09.802 --> 00:12.720
Finn's mom, Carole,
is dating Kurt's dad, Burt,
which was totally Kurt's idea.

00:12.805 --> 00:15.181
- But Kurt got mad that Burt
and Finn started hanging out.
- I miss you, Dad.

00:15.265 --> 00:17.517
Rachel hurt her voice
and couldn't sing.

00:17.601 --> 00:20.144
- She thought that was the only
thing that was important.
- I need applause to live.

00:20.229 --> 00:23.439
Finn introduced her to a friend who
showed her there's worse things
to lose than your voice.

00:23.524 --> 00:24.691
I compensate with humor.

00:24.775 --> 00:26.651
And that's what you missed on Glee.

00:28.404 --> 00:30.488
[School Bell Rings]
You wanted to see me?

00:30.572 --> 00:33.408
William, there's
someone I would like
to introduce you to.

00:33.492 --> 00:35.535
He's the newest member
of our school board,

00:35.619 --> 00:37.704
and he'd like
to speak to you.

00:37.788 --> 00:40.957
Will Schuester,
meet Mr. Bryan Ryan.

00:42.918 --> 00:44.919
- ♪♪ [Piano Intro]
- We've met.

00:45.003 --> 00:47.213
[Will Narrating]
Bryan Ryan.

00:47.297 --> 00:50.133
We went to school together,
and he made my life
a living hell.

00:50.217 --> 00:54.554
He was two years older,
dated every girl I liked,
got every solo.

00:54.638 --> 00:58.349
♪ Cheer up, sleepy Jean ♪

00:58.434 --> 01:01.102
♪ Oh, what can it mean ♪

01:01.186 --> 01:04.731
♪ To a daydream believer ♪

01:04.815 --> 01:11.696
- ♪ And a homecoming queen ♪
- [Kids Exclaiming]

01:11.780 --> 01:14.073
What's the matter, Schuester—
cat got your talent?

01:14.158 --> 01:15.658
[Chuckles]
[Kids Laugh]

01:15.743 --> 01:17.910
I'm here to do an audit
of our curriculum, Will.

01:17.995 --> 01:20.705
We may need to cut
some of our district's
art programs.

01:20.789 --> 01:22.999
It's really just a formality,
William.

01:23.083 --> 01:26.294
- No, it's not. We'll probably
cut the Glee Club.
- What?

01:26.378 --> 01:29.046
But-But you were
in the Glee Club.
Show choir was your life.

01:29.131 --> 01:30.882
It was, Will.

01:30.966 --> 01:33.593
And after I graduated,
I hit the big time.

01:33.677 --> 01:35.803
I was a featured soloist
at Kings Island...

01:35.888 --> 01:37.805
in the Doodledy-Do
Musical Review.

01:37.890 --> 01:39.390
We were a smash.

01:39.475 --> 01:42.977
Then, for three years,
I did the cruise ship circuit.

01:43.061 --> 01:47.106
And when that dried up,
I realized I had been sold
a bill of goods.

01:47.191 --> 01:51.486
Nine years later, I woke up
on a urine-stained mattress...

01:51.570 --> 01:53.780
in the West Lima crack district.

01:53.864 --> 01:56.949
Then... something
amazing happened.

01:58.786 --> 02:00.953
I was introduced to Jesus.

02:01.038 --> 02:03.122
He was my Honduran
social worker.

02:03.207 --> 02:05.166
I straightened up,
put down the pipe,

02:05.250 --> 02:07.210
met the love of my life- Wilma-

02:07.294 --> 02:09.712
and now I run a successful
used-Hummer dealership.

02:09.797 --> 02:12.673
Don't make that face.
Global warming's a theory.

02:13.884 --> 02:16.010
[Sighs]
And four nights a week,

02:16.094 --> 02:18.471
I run a show choir
conversion group.

02:18.555 --> 02:20.932
Hi. I'm Brenda.

02:21.016 --> 02:23.893
And it's been 42 days
since I sang a show tune.

02:23.977 --> 02:25.436
[Group]
Hi, Brenda.

02:25.521 --> 02:27.438
Years ago,
when I auditioned...

02:27.523 --> 02:30.650
to play Miss Adelaide
in Guys and Dolls,

02:30.734 --> 02:33.110
I was asked to take
my top off.

02:33.195 --> 02:35.530
Evidently,
that is not customary.

02:35.614 --> 02:39.909
And... that's when
I started huffing glue.

02:39.993 --> 02:42.787
My name is Russell.
I'm a glee club survivor.

02:42.871 --> 02:45.498
Whenever anything bad
would happen,

02:45.582 --> 02:48.584
I would just say,
"Let's put on a show."
Well, guess what.

02:48.669 --> 02:52.755
"Puttin' on a show"
about your father's
prostate cancer...

02:52.840 --> 02:56.008
will actually just
make him more depressed
about the situation.

02:56.093 --> 02:58.511
Show choir kills.

02:58.595 --> 03:00.847
I just want to have
a talk with your kids,

03:00.931 --> 03:04.308
make sure you're not
building up their hopes
just to have them knocked down.

03:04.393 --> 03:06.310
What if I say no?

03:06.395 --> 03:10.064
Just let him speak
to the kids, William.

03:10.148 --> 03:13.526
Let Mr. Bryan Ryan contribute
to the marketplace of ideas.

03:13.610 --> 03:16.153
What's the worst
that can happen?

03:16.238 --> 03:18.781
Okay, guys, listen up.
This is Mr. Ryan.

03:18.866 --> 03:20.783
He's a member
of the school board,

03:20.868 --> 03:22.743
and he would like
to say a few words.

03:24.037 --> 03:26.289
I-I just want you guys
to listen critically...

03:26.373 --> 03:30.293
and know that what he's saying
is just one of many opinions.

03:31.503 --> 03:34.422
Take out a piece of paper,
and, on that paper,

03:34.506 --> 03:38.134
I want you to write down
your biggest dream—

03:38.218 --> 03:43.931
a dream that means so much
you're afraid to admit it
even to yourself.

03:50.606 --> 03:53.941
Your dream is never
going to happen.

03:54.026 --> 03:58.905
Ninety-one percent of you
will spend your entire lives
living in Allen County, Ohio.

03:58.989 --> 04:01.157
So unless you wrote down
that your dream...

04:01.241 --> 04:03.492
was to work for a mid-market
health insurance provider...

04:03.577 --> 04:07.455
or find an entry-level job
in an elderly-care facility,

04:07.539 --> 04:09.123
you're going to be
very disappointed.

04:09.207 --> 04:11.751
This is really depressing.

04:11.835 --> 04:15.713
I'm going to guess that
a lot of your dreams
involve showbiz.

04:15.797 --> 04:17.506
Well, let me tell you,

04:17.591 --> 04:21.344
showbiz dreams are
the most unrealistic
of them all.

04:21.428 --> 04:24.430
But... that's what I want
to do with my life.

04:24.514 --> 04:29.101
Oh, look, I'm not trying
to hurt your feelings.

04:29.186 --> 04:31.187
I'm just trying
to spare you disappointment.

04:31.271 --> 04:32.396
I think we get your point.

04:32.481 --> 04:36.525
Aw, well, Schuester here's
a prime example.

04:36.610 --> 04:39.320
He used to have that glimmer
of hope in his eyes...

04:39.404 --> 04:41.572
that I can see right now
in all of yours.

04:41.657 --> 04:45.326
But... he couldn't make it
happen for himself,

04:45.410 --> 04:50.289
so he now has to try
and convince you all
that it'll happen for you.

04:50.374 --> 04:52.917
Guess what.
His dream didn't work out.

04:54.586 --> 04:57.129
And neither will yours.

04:57.214 --> 04:59.924
[Crying]

05:00.008 --> 05:03.177
Okay. You're done here.

05:03.261 --> 05:05.429
You would be wise
to show me some respect.

05:05.514 --> 05:09.058
You've said your piece.
Now get out.

05:09.142 --> 05:13.437
Well, Schuester,
I should thank you.

05:13.522 --> 05:16.649
You've made my decision
about which program to cut
a lot easier.

05:19.236 --> 05:20.903
[Sighs]

05:24.032 --> 05:26.492
[School Bell Rings]

05:28.286 --> 05:30.371
Thanks.

05:30.455 --> 05:32.498
"Godard on Godard"?

05:32.582 --> 05:35.584
He was the master
of the French New Wave.

05:35.669 --> 05:40.172
I was figuring that since
I'm never going to become
a star as a performer-

05:40.257 --> 05:41.757
[Exhales]

05:41.842 --> 05:44.802
maybe I could become one
behind the camera.

05:44.886 --> 05:47.263
You know Christopher Reeve
directed a movie
after his accident?

05:47.347 --> 05:48.931
- In the Gloaming.
- I didn't see it.

05:49.016 --> 05:50.725
Me neither.
Too depressing.

05:50.809 --> 05:53.269
Is that what you wrote
as your dream?

05:53.353 --> 05:57.773
Before Bryan Ryan crumpled it up
and tossed it in the trash? Yes.

05:57.858 --> 06:00.151
Why are you lying to me?

06:00.235 --> 06:03.237
[Tina]
After everybody left,
I went back for my book bag,

06:03.321 --> 06:06.240
and something stopped me.

06:06.324 --> 06:08.576
That was supposed
to be private.

06:08.660 --> 06:10.578
I don't understand you.

06:10.662 --> 06:12.538
You're always talking about
wanting to get with me,

06:12.622 --> 06:15.374
but you won't be honest with me
about your hopes and dreams.

06:15.459 --> 06:18.335
I'm in a wheelchair,
but I'm still a guy.

06:18.420 --> 06:21.630
What's the difference?
I'm never gonna actually
become a dancer.

06:21.715 --> 06:24.050
My legs are never
gonna work again.

06:24.134 --> 06:26.677
That was stupid.

06:28.096 --> 06:30.181
I was thinking.

06:30.265 --> 06:32.558
Mr. Schue was so busy
dealing with Bryan Ryan...

06:32.642 --> 06:34.643
that he didn't give us
an assignment for the week.

06:34.728 --> 06:39.065
So why don't we do one on our own?
A dance number.

06:39.149 --> 06:41.692
You wanna dance with me?

06:42.986 --> 06:44.737
You were pretty hot
in "Proud Mary."

06:44.821 --> 06:46.947
Why don't we try
and kick it up
a few notches?

06:47.032 --> 06:49.784
[Chuckles]

06:58.919 --> 07:00.836
Hi.

07:00.921 --> 07:03.089
Hi.

07:03.173 --> 07:06.884
How was
your spring break?

07:06.968 --> 07:08.886
Good.

07:09.930 --> 07:11.931
It's good to be back.

07:14.559 --> 07:16.477
What were you
just rehearsing?

07:16.561 --> 07:21.398
A guy came to Glee Club
to talk to us about dreams.

07:21.483 --> 07:23.734
Luckily, I've known mine
since I was four.

07:23.819 --> 07:25.444
I'm gonna play
three parts on Broadway-

07:25.529 --> 07:27.863
Evita, Funny Girl
and Laurey
in Oklahoma!

07:27.948 --> 07:30.658
I was just practicing
her dream ballet
with Curly.

07:30.742 --> 07:34.286
It's what I do when
I'm feeling a little stressed.
That's not a dream.

07:34.371 --> 07:37.164
A dream is something that
fills up the emptiness inside-

07:37.249 --> 07:40.876
the one thing that
you know if it came true,
all the hurt would go away.

07:40.961 --> 07:42.711
You singing
"Don't Cry for me, Argentina"...

07:42.796 --> 07:45.464
in front of a sold-out crowd
isn't a fantasy.

07:45.549 --> 07:47.508
It's an inevitability.

07:52.848 --> 07:55.349
[Chuckles]

07:55.433 --> 07:57.601
I thought you'd
never come back.

07:57.686 --> 08:01.438
And miss all your drama?
Never.

08:01.523 --> 08:02.982
[School Bell Rings]

08:03.066 --> 08:06.193
So, what is it?
Your dream.

08:06.278 --> 08:08.279
I don't know.

08:08.363 --> 08:12.158
Well, then go inside,
find it and ask it
what it's gonna take.

08:12.242 --> 08:14.160
Why are you pushing this?

08:14.244 --> 08:17.997
Because you're my girlfriend,
and I want to know all your secrets.

08:18.081 --> 08:20.082
When you lie awake at night,
what's missing?

08:21.209 --> 08:23.127
My mom.

08:23.211 --> 08:26.547
Your mom? You mean, like,
you want to meet her?

08:26.631 --> 08:30.134
I just would like
to know who she is.

08:30.218 --> 08:32.136
I don't really need
to meet her or anything,

08:32.220 --> 08:37.224
but maybe just find out her name
or... something about her.

08:37.309 --> 08:38.726
Hmm.

08:38.810 --> 08:40.895
It's silly.

08:40.979 --> 08:43.189
It's like— It's not like
it's gonna happen or anything.

08:43.315 --> 08:46.025
Why?
Just because my dads
never told me anything.

08:46.109 --> 08:48.027
And I didn't want
to ask them anything...

08:48.111 --> 08:50.404
'cause I didn't want
to hurt their feelings.

08:50.488 --> 08:52.489
So let's check it out
without them knowing.

08:53.617 --> 08:55.951
Do you know why
I came back to school here?

08:56.036 --> 08:58.579
To win another national title
and make all your dreams
come true.

08:58.663 --> 09:01.415
If this is one of them,
then I'm not gonna stop
until it happens.

09:04.044 --> 09:06.253
♪♪ [Piano: Medium Tempo]
[Taps Clicking]

09:06.338 --> 09:07.963
[Taps Click]

09:19.768 --> 09:21.602
[Clicking]

09:26.191 --> 09:28.734
♪♪ [Stops]

09:28.818 --> 09:30.736
My tap wheels suck.

09:30.820 --> 09:32.404
I thought we sounded
pretty good.

09:32.489 --> 09:34.406
Yeah, you did.

09:34.491 --> 09:37.701
I sound like someone
put tap shoes on a horse
and then shot it.

09:37.786 --> 09:40.204
Will you bring me those?

09:42.207 --> 09:44.667
I borrowed them
from John Hubener.

09:44.751 --> 09:47.836
- The kid with cerebral palsy?
- Yeah. They're his extra pair.

09:47.921 --> 09:49.838
Help me get up on them.

09:49.923 --> 09:52.007
Have you ever used
anything like these before?

09:52.092 --> 09:57.429
No, but I have superhuman
upper-body strength
from using my wheelchair.

09:57.514 --> 10:00.808
If I can just get up,
I think I can use my arms
to get around the room.

10:02.352 --> 10:05.771
Come on. You said we were
gonna kick it up a notch.

10:05.855 --> 10:07.856
Dreams aren't supposed
to be easy.

10:17.158 --> 10:19.368
I'm gonna try take a step.

10:23.081 --> 10:25.040
Artie, you're doing it.

10:28.920 --> 10:31.714
[Groans]
Are you okay?

10:31.798 --> 10:33.757
Go away.

10:33.842 --> 10:35.968
Let me bring
your chair over.

10:36.052 --> 10:38.762
Just go... away.

10:38.847 --> 10:40.764
You shouldn't have
done this to me.
You pushed me to do this.

10:40.849 --> 10:43.851
I'm sorry.

10:43.935 --> 10:45.936
Just go away, please.

10:47.480 --> 10:49.481
[Quietly]
Go away.

10:53.403 --> 10:57.072
- [School Bell Rings]
- Hey, Bryan.

10:57.157 --> 11:00.075
Hello, Will.
Just taking stock
of the home ec supplies.

11:00.160 --> 11:02.995
You see, our home ec program
teaches practical skills...

11:03.079 --> 11:05.664
like food service preparation.

11:05.749 --> 11:08.167
Can't feed a child
sheet music, Will.

11:08.251 --> 11:11.045
I suppose you could for a while, but...
they'd be dead in a month.

11:11.129 --> 11:13.380
- I'd like to buy you a beer.
- [Scoffs]

11:13.465 --> 11:16.967
No, no. I want to convince you
that you're wrong.

11:17.052 --> 11:19.386
- You won't.
- [Exhales]

11:20.430 --> 11:23.098
Then... for old times' sake?

11:28.438 --> 11:30.314
[School Bell Rings]

11:31.524 --> 11:34.360
[Whispering]
I found her.
Your mother? Where?

11:34.444 --> 11:36.737
In the library.

11:37.822 --> 11:39.740
I've been researching her
all morning,

11:39.824 --> 11:41.950
and, as I suspected,
my intuition has been
proven correct.

11:42.035 --> 11:45.996
My mother is Broadway legend
Patti LuPone.

11:46.081 --> 11:47.998
I've always had a deep
connection to Miss LuPone—

11:48.083 --> 11:50.292
her choice of roles and songs.

11:50.377 --> 11:53.921
I decided to do a little math
to see if her being my mother
was even possible.

11:54.005 --> 11:56.632
I was born December 18, 1994.

11:56.716 --> 11:59.176
1994 was a big year for Mother.

11:59.260 --> 12:01.720
She was a sensation in Pal Joey.

12:01.805 --> 12:03.972
But that was New York.
I was born in Ohio, you say.

12:04.057 --> 12:07.893
Well, Mother took many breaks
from the show to tour
with Mandy Patinkin.

12:07.977 --> 12:10.854
That April found them
at the EJ Thomas Hall
in Akron, Ohio,

12:10.939 --> 12:14.400
for a standing-room performance
nine months before I was born.

12:14.484 --> 12:17.986
Are you saying that your fathers
impregnated Patti LuPone
in the Marriott in Akron?

12:18.071 --> 12:19.780
Was Mandy Patinkin
in on this?

12:19.864 --> 12:21.865
All you have to do
is look at pictures of her...

12:21.950 --> 12:23.867
in her performance
in Master Class in 1996.

12:23.952 --> 12:27.037
Look at the pain in her eyes
and the hurt she's feeling...

12:27.122 --> 12:29.164
from giving up her obviously
talented little girl.

12:29.249 --> 12:31.750
One question.
What was in it for her?

12:31.835 --> 12:36.004
Mo-Money, a-a sense of charity
for those in need.

12:39.384 --> 12:43.220
No. I guess you're right.

12:43.304 --> 12:46.265
Do you want to hear my research
that proves that my mother
is Bernadette Peters?

12:46.349 --> 12:48.225
Why are you so afraid
about finding the truth?

12:48.309 --> 12:50.936
I don't know. I guess I just
don't want to think...

12:51.020 --> 12:53.605
that my mother's
some teenage trollop like Quinn...

12:53.690 --> 12:56.191
or, worse, some skanky girl
who would do anything for money,

12:56.276 --> 12:58.193
including giving me up.

12:58.278 --> 13:00.195
Why does it have to be
one of those choices?

13:00.280 --> 13:02.489
Maybe she had a really good reason
for doing what she did.

13:02.574 --> 13:04.533
We need to do
a real investigation,

13:04.617 --> 13:07.161
like CSI real.

13:07.245 --> 13:09.496
Do you have any baby stuff
in your house- something
that might give us a clue?

13:09.581 --> 13:11.957
My fathers kept
every piece of paper
related to my life...

13:12.041 --> 13:13.959
in files and cabinets
in our basement.

13:14.043 --> 13:15.794
It's sort of a little
Rachel Berry museum.

13:15.879 --> 13:20.174
Perfect.
We'll start there.

13:20.258 --> 13:24.303
- [Man] ♪ Oh, dream weaver ♪
- [Will] You were
a big deal at McKinley.

13:24.387 --> 13:29.183
- ♪ I believe you can get me
through the night ♪
- You had all the moves.

13:29.267 --> 13:30.976
You were one of those dudes...

13:31.060 --> 13:33.729
where all the guys
wanted to be you
and all the girls wanted you.

13:33.813 --> 13:35.981
Not all of them.

13:36.065 --> 13:38.817
Really? All right, who-
who was the one
that got away?

13:38.902 --> 13:41.653
Terri Delmonico.
Remember her?

13:41.738 --> 13:44.990
[Coughing]

13:45.074 --> 13:47.201
Yeah. Yeah, she was-
she was cool.

13:47.285 --> 13:49.036
I— I married her.

13:49.162 --> 13:52.289
No way.
Yeah.

13:52.373 --> 13:54.124
It didn't really
work out though.

13:54.209 --> 13:56.543
Wow. I'm sorry to hear that.

13:56.628 --> 13:58.837
She was great.
I really loved her.

13:58.922 --> 14:02.257
And, you know, just-
just grew apart.

14:03.593 --> 14:06.053
Do you know what
gave me the strength to...

14:06.137 --> 14:08.305
finally get out
of a terrible marriage?

14:10.099 --> 14:12.392
Music.

14:12.477 --> 14:15.521
Me and those kids—
coaching Glee Club.

14:15.605 --> 14:17.523
No, you're right.

14:17.607 --> 14:20.025
I'm— I'm never
gonna be on Broadway.

14:20.109 --> 14:22.110
And maybe the same
is gonna go for
most of those kids,

14:22.195 --> 14:25.113
but that's not the point.

14:25.198 --> 14:30.244
Glee Club- it's not
just about expressing
yourself to everyone else.

14:31.788 --> 14:33.789
It's about expressing
yourself to yourself.

14:33.873 --> 14:35.541
[Whimpers]

14:35.625 --> 14:37.751
I'm living a lie.

14:37.835 --> 14:39.211
What?

14:39.295 --> 14:42.381
[Crying]
I miss it so much.

14:42.465 --> 14:45.008
I am miserable.

14:45.093 --> 14:48.762
Ever since I stopped performing,
I cannot stand my life.

14:51.057 --> 14:53.934
Three times a year,
I tell my wife I'm going
off to a business trip.

14:54.018 --> 14:56.645
I sneak out to New York,
I see a bunch
of Broadway shows.

14:56.729 --> 15:01.149
I have a box of playbills hidden
away in my basement, Will,

15:01.234 --> 15:03.485
like porn.

15:03.570 --> 15:07.114
[Crying]

15:08.449 --> 15:11.076
The lit—
What are you doing?
[Coin Clatters]

15:11.160 --> 15:12.911
I'm— [Whimpers]

15:12.996 --> 15:16.665
♪♪ [Pop Ballad]
You remember?
Sectionals, 1992.

15:16.749 --> 15:19.501
You sang this song
alone on stage.
Just you and a piano.

